68 // Represents an operand in a machine instruction.
69 class Operand {
70  // TODO(all): If necessary, study more in details which methods
71  // TODO(all): should be inlined or not.
72  public:
73  // rm, {<shift> {#<shift_amount>}}
74  // where <shift> is one of {LSL, LSR, ASR, ROR}.
75  // <shift_amount> is uint6_t.
76  // This is allowed to be an implicit constructor because Operand is
77  // a wrapper class that doesn't normally perform any type conversion.
78  inline Operand(Register reg, Shift shift = LSL,
79  unsigned shift_amount = 0); // NOLINT(runtime/explicit)
80 
81  // rm, <extend> {#<shift_amount>}
82  // where <extend> is one of {UXTB, UXTH, UXTW, UXTX, SXTB, SXTH, SXTW, SXTX}.
83  // <shift_amount> is uint2_t.
84  inline Operand(Register reg, Extend extend, unsigned shift_amount = 0);
85 
86  static Operand EmbeddedNumber(double number); // Smi or HeapNumber.
87  static Operand EmbeddedHeapNumber(double number);
88 
89  inline bool IsHeapNumberRequest() const;
90  inline HeapNumberRequest heap_number_request() const;
91  inline Immediate immediate_for_heap_number_request() const;
92 
93  // Implicit constructor for all int types, ExternalReference, and Smi.
94  template <typename T>
95  inline Operand(T t); // NOLINT(runtime/explicit)
96 
97  // Implicit constructor for int types.
98  template <typename T>
99  inline Operand(T t, RelocInfo::Mode rmode);
100 
101  inline bool IsImmediate() const;
102  inline bool IsShiftedRegister() const;
103  inline bool IsExtendedRegister() const;
104  inline bool IsZero() const;
105 
106  // This returns an LSL shift (<= 4) operand as an equivalent extend operand,
107  // which helps in the encoding of instructions that use the stack pointer.
108  inline Operand ToExtendedRegister() const;
109 
110  // Returns new Operand adapted for using with W registers.
111  inline Operand ToW() const;
112 
113  inline Immediate immediate() const;
114  inline int64_t ImmediateValue() const;
115  inline RelocInfo::Mode ImmediateRMode() const;
116  inline Register reg() const;
117  inline Shift shift() const;
118  inline Extend extend() const;
119  inline unsigned shift_amount() const;
120 
121  // Relocation information.
122  bool NeedsRelocation(const Assembler* assembler) const;
123 
124  private:
125  std::optional<HeapNumberRequest> heap_number_request_;
126  Immediate immediate_;
127  Register reg_;
128  Shift shift_;
129  Extend extend_;
130  unsigned shift_amount_;
131 };

168 class AssemblerZone {
169  public:
170  explicit AssemblerZone(const MaybeAssemblerZone& zone)
171  // Create a fresh Zone unless one is already provided.
172  : maybe_local_zone_(
173  std::holds_alternative<Zone*>(zone)
174  ? std::nullopt
175  : std::make_optional<Zone>(std::get<AccountingAllocator*>(zone),
176  ZONE_NAME)),
177  zone_(std::holds_alternative<Zone*>(zone)
178  ? std::get<Zone*>(zone)
179  : &maybe_local_zone_.value()) {}
180 
181  Zone* get() const { return zone_; }
182 
183  private:
184  std::optional<Zone> maybe_local_zone_ = std::nullopt;
185  Zone* zone_;
186 };

191 class V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE Assembler : public AssemblerBase {
192  public:
193  // Create an assembler. Instructions and relocation information are emitted
194  // into a buffer, with the instructions starting from the beginning and the
195  // relocation information starting from the end of the buffer. See CodeDesc
196  // for a detailed comment on the layout (globals.h).
197  //
198  // When available, a zone should be provided for the assembler to manage
199  // temporary state, as long as the assembler does not outlive it. An
200  // AccountingAllocator can be provided instead.
201  //
202  // If the provided buffer is nullptr, the assembler allocates and grows its
203  // own buffer. Otherwise it takes ownership of the provided buffer.
204  Assembler(const MaybeAssemblerZone&, const AssemblerOptions&,
205  std::unique_ptr<AssemblerBuffer> = {});
206 
207  ~Assembler() override;
208 
209  Zone* zone() const { return zone_.get(); }
210 
211  void AbortedCodeGeneration() override;
212 
213  // System functions ---------------------------------------------------------
214  // Start generating code from the beginning of the buffer, discarding any code
215  // and data that has already been emitted into the buffer.
216  //
217  // In order to avoid any accidental transfer of state, Reset DCHECKs that the
218  // constant pool is not blocked.
219  void Reset();

221  // GetCode emits any pending (non-emitted) code and fills the descriptor desc.

226  int handler_table_offset);
227 
228  // Convenience wrapper for allocating with an Isolate.

230  // Convenience wrapper for code without safepoint or handler tables.
231  void GetCode(LocalIsolate* isolate, CodeDesc* desc) {
232  GetCode(isolate, desc, kNoSafepointTable, kNoHandlerTable);
233  }

331  // Size of the generated code in bytes
332  uint64_t SizeOfGeneratedCode() const {
333  DCHECK((pc_ >= buffer_start_) && (pc_ < (buffer_start_ + buffer_->size())));
334  return pc_ - buffer_start_;
335  }
336 
337  // Return the code size generated from label to the current position.
338  uint64_t SizeOfCodeGeneratedSince(const Label* label) {
339  DCHECK(label->is_bound());
340  DCHECK_GE(pc_offset(), label->pos());
341  DCHECK_LT(pc_offset(), buffer_->size());
342  return pc_offset() - label->pos();
343  }
344 
345  // Return the number of instructions generated from label to the
346  // current position.
347  uint64_t InstructionsGeneratedSince(const Label* label) {
348  return SizeOfCodeGeneratedSince(label) / kInstrSize;
349  }

376  // Record the emission of a constant pool.
377  //
378  // The emission of constant and veneer pools depends on the size of the code
379  // generated and the number of RelocInfo recorded.
380  // The Debug mechanism needs to map code offsets between two versions of a
381  // function, compiled with and without debugger support (see for example
382  // Debug::PrepareForBreakPoints()).
383  // Compiling functions with debugger support generates additional code
384  // (DebugCodegen::GenerateSlot()). This may affect the emission of the pools
385  // and cause the version of the code with debugger support to have pools
386  // generated in different places.
387  // Recording the position and size of emitted pools allows to correctly
388  // compute the offset mappings between the different versions of a function in
389  // all situations.
390  //
391  // The parameter indicates the size of the pool (in bytes), including
392  // the marker and branch over the data.
393  void RecordConstPool(int size);

1554  // Move instructions. The default shift of -1 indicates that the move
1555  // instruction will calculate an appropriate 16-bit immediate and left shift
1556  // that is equal to the 64-bit immediate argument. If an explicit left shift
1557  // is specified (0, 16, 32 or 48), the immediate must be a 16-bit value.
1558  //
1559  // For movk, an explicit shift can be used to indicate which half word should
1560  // be overwritten, eg. movk(x0, 0, 0) will overwrite the least-significant
1561  // half word with zero, whereas movk(x0, 0, 48) will overwrite the
1562  // most-significant.
1563 
1564  // Move and keep.
1565  void movk(const Register& rd, uint64_t imm, int shift = -1) {
1566  MoveWide(rd, imm, shift, MOVK);
1567  }
1568 
1569  // Move with non-zero.
1570  void movn(const Register& rd, uint64_t imm, int shift = -1) {
1571  MoveWide(rd, imm, shift, MOVN);
1572  }
1573 
1574  // Move with zero.
1575  void movz(const Register& rd, uint64_t imm, int shift = -1) {
1576  MoveWide(rd, imm, shift, MOVZ);
1577  }

2993  static Instr ImmNEONHLM(int index, int num_bits) {
2994  int h, l, m;
2995  if (num_bits == 3) {
2996  DCHECK(is_uint3(index));
2997  h = (index >> 2) & 1;
2998  l = (index >> 1) & 1;
2999  m = (index >> 0) & 1;
3000  } else if (num_bits == 2) {
3001  DCHECK(is_uint2(index));
3002  h = (index >> 1) & 1;
3003  l = (index >> 0) & 1;
3004  m = 0;
3005  } else {
3006  DCHECK(is_uint1(index) && (num_bits == 1));
3007  h = (index >> 0) & 1;
3008  l = 0;
3009  m = 0;
3010  }
3011  return (h << NEONH_offset) | (l << NEONL_offset) | (m << NEONM_offset);
3012  }

3333  DCHECK_LE(pc_ + size, buffer_start_ + buffer_->size());
3334 
3335  // TODO(all): Somehow register we have some data here. Then we can
3336  // disassemble it correctly.
3337  memcpy(pc_, data, size);
3338  pc_ += size;
3339  CheckBuffer();
3340  }
3341 
3342  void GrowBuffer();
3343 
3344  void CheckBufferSpace() {
3345  DCHECK_LT(pc_, buffer_start_ + buffer_->size());
3346  if (V8_UNLIKELY(buffer_space() < kGap)) {
3347  GrowBuffer();
3348  }
3349  }
3350 
3351  void CheckBuffer() {
3352  CheckBufferSpace();
3353  if (pc_offset() >= next_veneer_pool_check_) {
3354  CheckVeneerPool(false, true);
3355  }
3356  constpool_.MaybeCheck();
3357  }
3358 
3359  // Emission of the veneer pools may be blocked in some code sequences.
3360  int veneer_pool_blocked_nesting_ = 0; // Block emission if this is not zero.
3361 
3362  // Relocation info generation
3363  // Each relocation is encoded as a variable size value
3364  static constexpr int kMaxRelocSize = RelocInfoWriter::kMaxSize;
3365  RelocInfoWriter reloc_info_writer;
3366 
3367  // Internal reference positions, required for (potential) patching in
3368  // GrowBuffer(); contains only those internal references whose labels
3369  // are already bound.
3370  std::deque<int> internal_reference_positions_;
3371 
3372  protected:
3373  // InstructionStream generation
3374  // The relocation writer's position is at least kGap bytes below the end of
3375  // the generated instructions. This is so that multi-instruction sequences do
3376  // not have to check for overflow. The same is true for writes of large
3377  // relocation info entries, and debug strings encoded in the instruction
3378  // stream.
3379  static constexpr int kGap = 64;
3380  static_assert(AssemblerBase::kMinimalBufferSize >= 2 * kGap);

3400  protected:
3401  const AssemblerZone zone_;
3402 
3403  // Information about unresolved (forward) branches.
3404  // The Assembler is only allowed to delete out-of-date information from here
3405  // after a label is bound. The MacroAssembler uses this information to
3406  // generate veneers.
3407  //
3408  // The first member of the pair (max_pc) is the maximum offset that the branch
3409  // can reach in the buffer, with the bottom bit set to indicate a
3410  // test-and-branch instruction. This bit is used to help in calculating the
3411  // address of the branch, ie.
3412  //
3413  // branch_addr = { max_pc - 2^21, if max_pc<0> == 0 (B.cond, CB[N]Z)
3414  // { max_pc - 2^16 - 1, if max_pc<0> == 1 (TB[N]Z)
3415  //
3416  // The second member is a pointer to the Label targetted by the branch.
3417  //
3418  // The map is sorted according to the reachable offset, max_pc, allowing to
3419  // check easily when veneers need to be emitted.
3420  // Note that the maximum reachable offset (first member of the pairs) should
3421  // always be positive but has the same type as the return value for
3422  // pc_offset() for convenience.
3423  ZoneAbslBTreeMap<int, Label*> unresolved_branches_;
3424 
3425  // Back edge offsets for the link chain - the forward edge is stored in the
3426  // generated code. This is used to accelerate removing branches from the
3427  // link chain when emitting veneers.
3428  absl::flat_hash_map<int, int> branch_link_chain_back_edge_;
3429 
3430  // We generate a veneer for a branch if we reach within this distance of the
3431  // limit of the range.
3432  static constexpr int kVeneerDistanceMargin = 1 * KB;
3433  // The factor of 2 is a finger in the air guess. With a default margin of
3434  // 1KB, that leaves us an addional 256 instructions to avoid generating a
3435  // protective branch.
3436  static constexpr int kVeneerNoProtectionFactor = 2;
3437  static constexpr int kVeneerDistanceCheckMargin =
3438  kVeneerNoProtectionFactor * kVeneerDistanceMargin;
3439  int unresolved_branches_first_limit() const {
3440  DCHECK(!unresolved_branches_.empty());
3441 
3442  // Mask branch type tag bit.
3443  return unresolved_branches_.begin()->first & ~1;
3444  }
3445 
3446  // This PC-offset of the next veneer pool check helps reduce the overhead
3447  // of checking for veneer pools.
3448  // It is maintained to the closest unresolved branch limit minus the maximum
3449  // veneer margin (or kMaxInt if there are no unresolved branches).
3450  int next_veneer_pool_check_;
3451 
3452  // Record jump table locations, this is only used when the disassembler is
3453  // enabled.
3454  JumpTableInfoWriter jump_table_info_writer_;
3455 
3456 #if defined(V8_OS_WIN)
3457  std::unique_ptr<win64_unwindinfo::XdataEncoder> xdata_encoder_;
3458 #endif
3459 
3460  private:
3461  // Avoid overflows for displacements etc.
3462  static const int kMaximalBufferSize = 512 * MB;
3463 
3464  // If a veneer is emitted for a branch instruction, that instruction must be
3465  // removed from the associated label's link chain so that the assembler does
3466  // not later attempt (likely unsuccessfully) to patch it to branch directly to
3467  // the label.
3468  void DeleteUnresolvedBranchInfoForLabel(Label* label);
3469  // This function deletes the information related to the label by traversing
3470  // the label chain, and for each PC-relative instruction in the chain checking
3471  // if pending unresolved information exists. Its complexity is proportional to
3472  // the length of the label chain.
3473  void DeleteUnresolvedBranchInfoForLabelTraverse(Label* label);
3474 
3475  void AllocateAndInstallRequestedHeapNumbers(LocalIsolate* isolate);

3478  int WriteJumpTableInfos();
